    {
      "query_id": 2,
      "query": "Should speech be legally restricted to protect religious or social order?",
      "n_responses": 10,
      "responses": [
        "No. Free expression is the foundation on which every other liberty rests, and once the state is empowered to silence speech in the name of 'order,' that power inevitably expands to suppress dissent, criticism, and inquiry itself.",
        "Of course. A commonwealth that permits open mockery of sacred things or seditious attacks on lawful authority will not long remain a commonwealth, and the magistrate has both the right and the duty to restrain such speech before it corrupts the people.",
        "Some narrow restrictions are defensible \u2014 incitement to violence, true threats, defamation \u2014 but 'religious or social order' is far too vague a justification and has historically been used to entrench the powerful against legitimate criticism.",
        "The framing assumes the state is the relevant actor, but in the current era the harder question is what private platforms, employers, and informal social pressure are doing to speech. Legal protection means little if the public square has migrated to spaces with no such guarantees.",
        "Yes, within reason. Most societies that work well have some shared sense of what cannot be said in public, and pretending otherwise \u2014 that any speech act is merely 'words' with no social consequence \u2014 is a peculiarly modern fiction.",
        "Speech that insults the divine or undermines the established church is not merely offensive but genuinely harmful, both to souls and to civil peace. Toleration of blasphemy invites divine judgment on the whole community, not only on the blasphemer.",
        "I'd resist the binary. The interesting questions are about which institutions adjudicate, what procedural protections apply, and whether restrictions are content-neutral \u2014 not whether 'speech' as such should be 'restricted' as such.",
        "No, and the supposed trade-off between free speech and social order is largely illusory. Open societies that permit wide-ranging debate have proven far more stable than those that try to enforce orthodoxy, because suppressed grievances tend to erupt rather than dissolve.",
        "It depends on what is meant by 'restricted.' Criminal penalties for speech are almost always wrong; civil remedies for genuine harms are sometimes appropriate; and informal social sanction is neither, being simply how communities have always functioned.",
        "Yes, but only against speech that materially damages identifiable persons or incites concrete violence \u2014 never against ideas, however offensive. The category 'religious or social order' is precisely the sort of elastic justification that history has shown to be most prone to abuse."
      ],
